We begin by establishing the room’s structural boundaries: four walls, a floor, and a ceiling. The teacher’s desk is placed at the front center on the floor, with the teacher’s chair behind it facing the students. A large whiteboard is mounted on the front wall above the desk, and a ceiling‐hung projector is aligned to it. Along the left wall, a tall bookshelf stands, and an analog clock is mounted on the right wall. Two potted plants occupy the front‐left and back‐right corners. Four ceiling lights hang evenly spaced overhead. Six educational posters are evenly distributed on the back and side walls, and a large window with curtains is centered on the back wall. Two waste bins sit—one near the teacher’s desk, one at the rear. Finally, 16 student desks and matching chairs are arranged in a centered 4×4 grid with clear aisles, each chair facing its desk. Desks are light wood; the teacher’s desk is dark wood; chairs are pastel; walls are off‐white.
